content:
Being #Black and #queer is beautiful. I wouldn‚Äôt trade it for anything. I‚Äôd rather not even exist if I couldn‚Äôt be Black #Mexican and Queer. With that said you bitches make this shit exhausting, I can‚Äôt stand the concept of whiteness. Like at all. It‚Äôs the friction that slows my ascension to greatness on a daily basis. I also find myself forever frustrated by people who act like they don‚Äôt recognize the difference between white people and the concept of whiteness. Cuz they absolutely seem to get the difference between Black people and the concept of Blackness and remind us of it everyday. I can only imagine what I‚Äôd accomplish if I didn‚Äôt have to waste so much energy navigating a society that quite literally never intended to include me.

Shout out to all the allies on #Mastodon #Today üíú

content:
Unsurprisingly, John's the only Black character listed in the 1976 DC Calendar, speaking to superhero comics' diversity at the time.

Again, wonder what a modern version of this calendar would be like, besides obviously having more people of color. Though suspect one-third to one-half would be Batman/Gotham-related at minimum; no war/western comics; and probably reference mainly recent/current storylines.

The neighbour's pennant through my window

The winds are rising, smell of water
These are storm signs

I will still go out
There is a conversation I must have
that only pines can know

content: Heh, small victory in a kerfuffle with a chinese PCB supplier. I sent them a panel with a bunch of variations of the same layout. The supplier came back asking for three times the amount of money I already paid for the order since the files "contained more than one design". I ended up adding a ground pour and some random useless traces to the tooling area around the layouts, and replacing V-cuts with mouse bites, and apparently now they're happy and sent the files to production. #electronics

content:
This isn't just me being pedantic.

The strategic misuse of the word "counterfeiting" appears to be a big reason why GBC (and firms that copied its litigation model) have been able to get courts to grant extraordinary relief on what appears to be a regular basis.

For more on why this language issue matters, see: https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4549909

The birds are high in the sky, so initially they seem like geese or shadows that rise, bank, and turn in fluid synchrony. The camera pans in (though we are still far away), and you can discern the unmistakably broad, saurian, large-billed silhouettes of the pelicans as they fly across the sky, then bank again and fly away off camera to the right. Partway through, in the center of the pelican scrum, one pelican seems to bump into another, wheeling back and dropping eir legs as e falls out of sync with the rest before regaining eir place in the swailing pod. Hello! I\'m a former #academic who still considers himself a #historian. While I\'ve left #academia behind, I still work as a #writer, mostly of essays and history pieces. Some of my pieces can be found in Jacobin, Teen Vogue, Smithsonian, and Belt. My PhD is in #history, and I studied the anti-apartheid movement in the United States. \u2029Today, I write about a variety of topics. When I can, I listen to #music and play #games.
